            <p>June 9<hi rend="sup">th</hi>&#44; 5650<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>The Hebrew letter you<lb/> gave me to read contains the de&#45;<lb/>&#45;scription of one Reuben Wallman<lb/> or Wollman of Kishinew&#44; Russia<lb/> who has left his wife &#34;Bathsheba&#34;<lb/> with three children and gone to<lb/> America with another woman.<lb/>  His wife desires your aid in procuring<lb/> from him a &#91;Hebrew&#93; and payment of the<lb/> support of herself and children<lb/> for the last two years.  Full par&#45;<lb/>&#45;ticulars and the whereabouts of the husband<lb/> can be ascertained of Mr Cohen<lb/> No 115 New Str Phila. who is acquaint&#45;<lb/>&#45;ed with the family and with<lb/> all the circumstances.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>The letter is written in a very<lb/> pathetic strain and the case<lb/> seems to be a very sad one.<lb/>  I remain<lb/> very respectfully<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
